We use a similar approach for Products,
replacing each out-going edge with a color
associated with that tensor.
If the individual tensors have symmetries,
we may have to replace them with a subgraph
representing this symmetry. (Actually this was
also the case for the sum.) This happens even
if the individual tensors are variables, since
variables can also have symmetries now.
For this we can use Frucht's theorem, which
creates, from any group, a graph with that
group as its automorphism group.
Note that this gives us a nice recursive structure
where we can compute the automorphisms of each
tensor in the Product depth first, and then combine
them.
One thing I wonder about is: Nauty finds the
permutations that you can apply to the entire graph.
But I only care about the "border nodes". Can I
easily "restrict" the group to just these? That would
also reduce the work involved in Frucht's theorem,
which I'm slightly worried about could be large, as
it constructs the entire Cauley graph. This graph,
on a subgraph of Sn could have 2n elements. So it
would be nice to limit n.
Note that the outer nodes should never be "confusable"
with inner nodes (as they are the only nodes with degree 1,
and also they have their own private color), so their
symmetries should already be a subgroup of the main
automorphism group. So I guess I can just use subgroup-
search again...
The "large frucht graph" problem is real though.
What if I just had each tensor return a structural graph
instead? Then just vf2 for everything...
Note that real graphs can't have "hanging edges"
so we add some dummy "stopper nodes" at the ends.
These won't get confused with copy nodes, since
Copy's have their own private color.
In both the sum and product case, all we are really
interested in is the overall canonicalization (hash) of
the graph, the symmetry group on the gray (outer)
nodes, and (though they follow) the orbits on these.
Btw, maybe not all tensors need the "construction"
with colored nodes on each of their outgoing edges...
it could simply be the necessary construction for
Variables, but general tensors can just use their
Frucht graph directly...
